{"title_page": "White slave propaganda", "text_new": "[[File:White slavery woodcut.jpg|thumb|upright=1.8|A woodcut (based on a photograph) that was published in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'' on 30 January 1864 with the caption, \"EMANCIPATED SLAVES, WHITE AND COLORED.\"]]\n'''White slave propaganda''' is the term given to publicity, especially photograph and woodcuts, and also novels, articles, and popular lectures, about mixed-race, white-looking slaves, which was used during and prior to the [[American Civil War]] to further the [[abolitionist]] cause and to raise money for the education of former slaves. The images included children with predominantly European features photographed alongside dark-skinned adult slaves with typically African features. It was intended to shock the viewing audiences with a reminder that slaves shared their humanity, and evidence that slaves did not belong in the category of the \"[[Other (philosophy)|Other]]\".\n\n==Historical background==\nSexual exploitation of slaves by their masters, master's sons, overseers, or other powerful white men was so common in the United States as to be routine. (See [[Children of the plantation]].) By the [[1860 Census]], mixed-race slaves constituted about 10% of the 4 million slaves enumerated; they were more numerous in the Upper South. Slavery had existed for a longer time there, and in the generally smaller holdings, slaves had lived more closely with white workers and masters, leading to more contact with whites. About 5% of slaves born in the [[Southern U.S.]] are believed to have been fathered by white masters.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} <!--Genetic analysis of African Americans shows high proportion of European ancestry - use that instead; Henry Louis Gates Jr's book has data on this --> \n\nAn analysis of the [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] [[Slave Narrative Collection]], collected in the 1930s, shows that, when women discussed parentage at all, about one-third of these women ex-slaves said they had given birth to a child with a white father, or were themselves the child of a white father.<ref>{{cite web|title=Free at Last? Slavery in Pittsburgh in the 18th and 19th Centuries|url=http://www.library.pitt.edu/freeatlast/fugitive_laws.html|website=University Library System|publisher=University of Pittsburgh|accessdate=July 7, 2016|date=2009}}</ref> The plight of these mixed-race slaves, especially as children, was often publicized as a way to further the abolitionist cause.\n\nThere were also public statements by pro-slavery activists who wanted slavery legalized nationwide, overruling state prohibitions, and that there was no reason why slavery was limited to blacks. According to them, Northern white laborers would have better lives as slaves.<ref name=\"Nye\">{{cite article\n|title=The Slave Power Conspiracy: 1830\u20131860\n|first=Russel B.\n|last=Nye\n|journal=[[Science & Society]]\n|volume=10\n|number=3\n|date=Summer 1946\n|pages=262\u2013274\n|jstor=40399768}}</ref>\n\n==Abolitionist use of \"white slaves\"==\n===Fiction===\nThe first abolitionist novel<ref name=\"Nye\" />, ''The Slave: or Memoirs of Archy Moore'', published in 1836 by then famous historian [[Richard Hildreth]], features an enslaved hero, son of a white planter and an enslaved mother, who is herself the daughter of a white planter, so that he can state that \"both on the father's and the mother's side, I had running in my veins, the best blood of Virginia\".<ref>{{citation|title=The Slave: or Memoirs of Archy Moore|at=p.&nbsp;19|language=en|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/moore1/moore1.html#p19|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> When he decides to escape together with his sister, they have no problems \"in passing ourselves as white citizens\",<ref>{{citation|title=The Slave: or Memoirs of Archy Moore|at=p.&nbsp;62|language=en|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/moore1/moore1.html#p62|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and the title of the extended edition of 1852 makes a reference to the whiteness of the hero: ''The White Slave; or, Memoirs of a Fugitive''.<ref>{{citation|title=The White Slave; or, Memoirs of a Fugitive|at=p.&nbsp;62|language=en|url=https://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/hildreth/menu.html|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe character of Eliza in the 1852 novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'' was described as a [[quadroon]] slave (\u00bc black ancestry), whose child also appeared to be \"all-but-white\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stowe|first1=Harriet Beecher|title=Uncle Tom's Cabin|publisher=George Routledge & Company|date=1852|page=[https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabin09stowgoog/page/n22 20]|url=https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabin09stowgoog|accessdate=July 5, 2016}} See, in particular, Chapter II</ref><ref name=\"Goodman\">{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Carol|title=\"As White As Their Masters\": Visualizing the Color Line|url=http://www.mirrorofrace.org/carol.html|website=mirrorofrace.org|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother popular abolitionist novel of the time was [[Mary Hayden Pike]]'s ''Ida May: a Story of Things Actual and Possible'' (1854), a story about a \"white\" slave. In 1855, [[Mary Mildred Williams|Mary Mildred Botts]], a young white slave, gained freedom with the help of Senator [[Charles Sumner]] of Massachusetts, who adopted her. She was considered the embodiment of Ida May. Articles were published about her in the ''[[Boston Telegraph]]'' and the [[New York Times]], and copies of her photograph were widely publicized.<ref>{{cite news|title=A White Slave from Virginia.|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B0CE4D6133DE034BC4153DFB566838E649FDE&legacy=true|accessdate=July 5, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=March 9, 1855}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gage|first1=Joan|title=A White Slave Girl \"Mulatto Raised by Charles Sumner\"|url=http://mirrorofrace.org/joan-gage/|website=Mirror of Race|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ida May\">{{cite web|last1=Morgan-Owens|first1=Jessie|title=Poster Child: There's Something About Mary|url=http://www.morgan-owens.com/blog/2015/2/18/theres-something-about-mary|publisher=Massachusetts Historical Society|accessdate=July 6, 2016|date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Botts appeared on stage during speeches by Sumner and other abolitionists. On May 19 and 20, 1856, Sumner spoke in the Senate, comparing Southern political positions to the sexual exploitation of slaves then taking place in the South. Two days later [[Caning of Charles Sumner|Sumner was beaten almost to death]] on the floor of the Senate in the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]] by Representative [[Preston Brooks]] from Georgia, known as a hothead.<ref name=\"Ida May\"/>\n\nThree decades after the [[Emancipation Proclamation]], [[Frances Harper]]'s 1892 novel ''[[Iola Leroy, or Shadows Uplifted]]'' tells the story of a \"colored\" family before and after emancipation. With the exception of Iola's grandmother, who is \"unmistakably colored\",<ref>{{citation|title=Iola Leroy, or Shadows Uplifted|at=p.&nbsp;206|language=en|url=https://docsouth.unc.edu/southlit/harper/harper.html#p206|access-date=2020-04-13\n}}</ref> all members of the family have so much European ancestry that they can easily [[Passing (racial identity)|pass for white]]. When Iola's uncle, Robert Johnson, escapes from slavery and distinguishes himself in the Union army, a white officer compares him to the other former slaves among his soldiers: \"You do not look like them, you do not talk like them. It is a burning shame to have held such a man as you in slavery.\" Johnson answers: \"I don't think it was any worse to have held me in slavery than the blackest man in the South.\"<ref>{{citation|title=Iola Leroy, or Shadows Uplifted|at=p.&nbsp;44|language=en|url=https://docsouth.unc.edu/southlit/harper/harper.html#p44|access-date=2020-04-13\n}}</ref>\n\n===Nonfiction===\nNonfiction accounts written by escaped mixed-race slaves who used their European appearance to \"pass for white\" and gain freedom include [[Ellen Craft]]: ''Running a Thousand Miles for Freedom'' (coauthored with her husband William).<ref name=\"Craft\">{{cite book|last1=Craft|first1=William and Ellen|title=Running a Thousand Miles for Freedom|date=1860|pages=63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0znsAgAAQBAJ|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> With majority-white ancestry, Craft often also appeared as a speaker on the abolitionist lecture circuit.<ref name=\"McCaskill\">[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-622 Barbara McCaskill, \"William and Ellen Craft\"], ''New Georgia Encyclopedia'', 2010, accessed July 6, 2016</ref>\n\nThe Crafts and other abolitionists also publicized the life of [[Sally Miller|Salom\u00e9 M\u00fcller]], a German immigrant orphaned as an infant soon after arrival in New Orleans. Though Muller (later known as Sally Miller) was completely of European descent, she became enslaved as an infant, treated as a mixed-race slave. The threat of white girls being seized and thrown into slavery prompted [[Parker Pillsbury]] to write to [[William Lloyd Garrison]]: \"A white skin is no security whatsoever. I should no more dare to send white children out to play alone, especially at night...than I should dare send them into a forest of tigers and hyenas.\"<ref name=\"Wilson\">[https://www.jstor.org/pss/4233569 Carol Wilson, \"Sally Muller, the White Slave\"], ''Louisiana History'', Vol. 40, 1999, accessed July 7, 2016</ref>\n\nFannie Virginia Casseopia Lawrence was a young white slave freed in early 1863. She was adopted by Catherine S. Lawrence of New York and baptized by [[Henry Ward Beecher]] at the Plymouth Congregational Church in Brooklyn, New York. ''Carte de visite'' photographs of her were also sold to raise money for the abolitionist cause.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Tanya Ballard|title=A Black And White 1860s Fundraiser|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/pictureshow/2012/12/10/166093470/a-black-and-white-1860s-fundraiser|website=NPR|accessdate=July 5, 2016|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=250>\nFile:Mary Mildred Botts.jpg|Mary Mildred Botts in an 1855 [[daguerreotype]]\nFile:Fannie Virginia Casseopia Lawrence 1863.jpg|Fannie Virginia Casseopia Lawrence, a slave freed in early 1863\nFile:Ellen Craft escaped slave.jpg|Etching of Ellen Craft based on a c. 1860 photo\n</gallery>\n\n===A special case: Freed slaves from Louisiana===\n[[File:Learning is Wealth.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Four former slaves - three children and an adult man, all with books in their hands; the image is entitled \"Learning is Wealth\"]]\n\nBy 1863 in Louisiana, ninety-five schools for [[freedmen]], serving 9,500 students, were active in areas controlled by the [[Union Army]]. Funding was needed to continue to run the schools. The [[National Freedman's Association]], the [[American Missionary Association]], and Union officers launched a publicity campaign to raise money by selling [[carte de visite]] (CDV) photographs of eight former slaves, five children and three adults. The former slaves were accompanied on a tour of Philadelphia and New York by Colonel [[George H. Hanks]]. A woodcut, based on a photograph of the former slaves, appeared in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'' in January 1864 with the caption \"EMANCIPATED SLAVES, WHITE AND COLORED.\"<ref name=CaustEllenbogen>{{cite web|last=Caust-Ellenbogen|first=Celia|title=White Slaves|url=http://trilogy.brynmawr.edu/speccoll/quakersandslavery/commentary/themes/white_slaves.php|publisher=[[Bryn Mawr College]], [[Swarthmore College]] |accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodman\" /> Four of the children were predominantly white in appearance, although born into slavery. \n\nThe former slaves traveled from [[New Orleans]] to the North. Of these, four children appeared to be white or [[octoroon]]. According to the ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'' article, they were, {{\" '}}perfectly white;' 'very fair;' 'of unmixed white race.' Their light complexions contrasted sharply with those of the three adults, Wilson, Mary, and Robert; and that of the fifth child, Isaac\u2014'a black boy of eight years; but nonetheless [more] intelligent than his whiter companions.{{' \"}}<ref name=CaustEllenbogen /><ref name=NYDN>{{cite news|title='White' slave children of New Orleans|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/white-slave-children-new-orleans-1860s-propaganda-campaign-gallery-1.1164989|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe group was accompanied by Colonel Hanks from the [[18th Infantry Regiment (United States)|18th Infantry Regiment]]. They posed for photos in [[New York City]] and in [[Philadelphia]]. The resulting images were produced in the [[carte de visite]] format and were sold for twenty-five cents each, with the profits of the sale being directed to [[Major general (United States)|Major General]] [[Nathaniel P. Banks]] back in [[Louisiana]] to support education of freedmen. Each of the photos noted that sale proceeds would be \"devoted to the education of colored people\".<ref name=CaustEllenbogen /><ref name=NYDN />\n\nOf the many prints that were commissioned, at least twenty-two remain in existence today. Most of these were produced by Charles Paxson and Myron Kimball, who took the group photo that later appeared as a woodcut in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]''. A portrait of Rebecca was taken by James E. McClees of Philadelphia.<ref name=CaustEllenbogen />\n\n==Modern analysis==\n[[File:Freedoms Banner Charley a slave boy from New Orelans 1864.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Charley Taylor holding an American flag.  Charley was the son of [[Alexander Withers]] and one of Withers's slaves.  Withers sold Charley to a slave dealer and he was sold again in New Orleans.]]\n\nModern scholars have examined the white slave campaign's motives and success. Mary Niall Mitchell, in \"Rosebloom and Pure White, Or So It Seemed,\"<ref name=\"mnm\">{{cite web|last1=Mitchell|first1=Mary Niall|title='Rosebloom and Pure White,' Or So It Seemed|url=http://scholarworks.uno.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1003&context=hist_facpubs|website=ScholarWorks@UNO|publisher=University of New Orleans|accessdate=June 29, 2016}} also published in  American Quarterly 54:3 (September 2002): 369-410</ref> argues that because the slaves were depicted as being white, through both their skin color and style of dress, abolitionists could argue that the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] was independent of class status. Supporters of the war believed that this was needed after [[New York City draft riots|the draft riots]] in [[New York City]] that year. Predominantly ethnic Irish mobs had protested the draft law, as wealthier men could buy substitutes rather than serve in the war.\n\nCarol Goodman, in \"Visualizing the Color Line,\" has argued that the photos alluded to physical and sexual abuse of the children's mothers. When publishing the photo of the eight former slaves, the editor of ''Harper's Weekly'' wrote that slavery permits slave-holding \"'gentlemen' [to] seduce [the] most friendless and defenseless of women.\" The specter of \"white\" girls being sold as \"fancy girls\" or [[concubines]] in Southern slave markets may have caused Northern families to fear for the safely of their own daughters. Similarly, the idea that white slave-master fathers would sell their own children in slave markets raised Northerners' concerns.\n\n[[Gwendolyn DuBois Shaw]], in \"Portraits of a People,\" has argued that the usage of props, such as the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] and books, helped to provide context for Northern viewers, and also to emphasize that the purpose of the photos was to raise money for education of former slaves by funding schools in [[Louisiana]]. She also noted that the use of \"white\" children to illustrate the damage caused by institutional slavery, whose victims were overwhelmingly visibly people of color, demonstrated the contemporary racism of both Southern and Northern societies.<ref name=CaustEllenbogen />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Julia Chinn]]\n*[[Louisa Picquet]]\n*[[Mary Mildred Williams]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenzer|first1=Lawrence Raymond|title=The Forgotten Cause of the Civil War: A New Look at the Slavery Issue|date=1997|publisher=Scholars' Publishing House|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EGkOAQAAMAAJ}} See especially [http://multiracial.com/site/index.php/2001/10/01/white-slaves/ Ch.III]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=p5U-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA32-IA29&lpg=PA32-IA29#v=onepage&q&f=false Fremont Campaign Literature, 1856]\n*[[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], [http://www.theroot.com/articles/history/2013/02/how_mixed_are_african_americans/ Exactly How \u2018Black\u2019 Is Black America?]\n*{{cite book|last1=Janken|first1=Kenneth Robert|title=Walter White: Mr. NAACP|date=2006|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=9780807857809|pages=3\u20135|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cTVZ6N9vHxsC}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|White slave propaganda}}\n{{Wikisource-inline|The Barbarism of Slavery}}\n*[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/white-slave-children-new-orleans-1860s-propaganda-campaign-gallery-1.1164989?pmSlide=0 Image gallery]\n\n[[Category:Abolitionism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Colorism]]\n[[Category:Propaganda in the United States]]\n[[Category:Skin pigmentation]]\n[[Category:Slavery in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:White slavery woodcut.jpg|thumb|upright=1.8|A woodcut (based on a photograph) that was published in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'' on 30 January 1864 with the caption, \"EMANCIPATED SLAVES, WHITE AND COLORED.\"]]\n'''White slave propaganda''' is the term given to publicity, especially photograph and woodcuts, and also novels, articles, and popular lectures, about mixed-race, white-looking slaves, which was used during and prior to the [[American Civil War]] to further the [[abolitionist]] cause and to raise money for the education of former slaves. The images included children with predominantly European features photographed alongside dark-skinned adult slaves with typically African features. It was intended to shock the viewing audiences with a reminder that slaves shared their humanity, and evidence that slaves did not belong in the category of the \"[[Other (philosophy)|Other]]\".\n\n==Historical background==\nSexual exploitation of slaves by their masters, master's sons, overseers, or other powerful white men was so common in the United States as to be routine. (See [[Children of the plantation]].) By the [[1860 Census]], mixed-race slaves constituted about 10% of the 4 million slaves enumerated; they were more numerous in the Upper South. Slavery had existed for a longer time there, and in the generally smaller holdings, slaves had lived more closely with white workers and masters, leading to more contact with whites. About 5% of slaves born in the [[Southern U.S.]] are believed to have been fathered by white masters.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} <!--Genetic analysis of African Americans shows high proportion of European ancestry - use that instead; Henry Louis Gates Jr's book has data on this --> \n\nAn analysis of the [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] [[Slave Narrative Collection]], collected in the 1930s, shows that, when women discussed parentage at all, about one-third of these women ex-slaves said they had given birth to a child with a white father, or were themselves the child of a white father.<ref>{{cite web|title=Free at Last? Slavery in Pittsburgh in the 18th and 19th Centuries|url=http://www.library.pitt.edu/freeatlast/fugitive_laws.html|website=University Library System|publisher=University of Pittsburgh|accessdate=July 7, 2016|date=2009}}</ref> The plight of these mixed-race slaves, especially as children, was often publicized as a way to further the abolitionist cause.\n\nThere were also public statements by pro-slavery activists who wanted slavery legalized nationwide, overruling state prohibitions, and that there was no reason why slavery was limited to blacks. According to them, Northern white laborers would have better lives as slaves.<ref name=\"Nye\">{{cite article\n|title=The Slave Power Conspiracy: 1830\u20131860\n|first=Russel B.\n|last=Nye\n|journal=[[Science & Society]]\n|volume=10\n|number=3\n|date=Summer 1946\n|pages=262\u2013274\n|jstor=40399768}}</ref>\n\n==Abolitionist use of \"white slaves\"==\n===Fiction===\nThe first abolitionist novel<ref name=\"Nye\" />, ''The Slave: or Memoirs of Archy Moore'', published in 1836 by then famous historian [[Richard Hildreth]], features an enslaved hero, son of a white planter and an enslaved mother, who is herself the daughter of a white planter, so that he can state that \"both on the father's and the mother's side, I had running in my veins, the best blood of Virginia\".<ref>{{citation|title=The Slave: or Memoirs of Archy Moore|at=p.&nbsp;19|language=en|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/moore1/moore1.html#p19|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> When he decides to escape together with his sister, they have no problems \"in passing ourselves as white citizens\",<ref>{{citation|title=The Slave: or Memoirs of Archy Moore|at=p.&nbsp;62|language=en|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/moore1/moore1.html#p62|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and the title of the extended edition of 1852 makes a reference to the whiteness of the hero: ''The White Slave; or, Memoirs of a Fugitive''.<ref>{{citation|title=The White Slave; or, Memoirs of a Fugitive|at=p.&nbsp;62|language=en|url=https://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/hildreth/menu.html|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe character of Eliza in the 1852 novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'' was described as a [[quadroon]] slave (\u00bc black ancestry), whose child also appeared to be \"all-but-white\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stowe|first1=Harriet Beecher|title=Uncle Tom's Cabin|publisher=George Routledge & Company|date=1852|page=[https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabin09stowgoog/page/n22 20]|url=https://archive.org/details/uncletomscabin09stowgoog|accessdate=July 5, 2016}} See, in particular, Chapter II</ref><ref name=\"Goodman\">{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Carol|title=\"As White As Their Masters\": Visualizing the Color Line|url=http://www.mirrorofrace.org/carol.html|website=mirrorofrace.org|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother popular abolitionist novel of the time was [[Mary Hayden Pike]]'s ''Ida May: a Story of Things Actual and Possible'' (1854), a story about a \"white\" slave. In 1855, [[Mary Mildred Williams|Mary Mildred Botts]], a young white slave, gained freedom with the help of Senator [[Charles Sumner]] of Massachusetts, who adopted her. She was considered the embodiment of Ida May. Articles were published about her in the ''[[Boston Telegraph]]'' and the [[New York Times]], and copies of her photograph were widely publicized.<ref>{{cite news|title=A White Slave from Virginia.|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B0CE4D6133DE034BC4153DFB566838E649FDE&legacy=true|accessdate=July 5, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=March 9, 1855}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gage|first1=Joan|title=A White Slave Girl \"Mulatto Raised by Charles Sumner\"|url=http://mirrorofrace.org/joan-gage/|website=Mirror of Race|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ida May\">{{cite web|last1=Morgan-Owens|first1=Jessie|title=Poster Child: There's Something About Mary|url=http://www.morgan-owens.com/blog/2015/2/18/theres-something-about-mary|publisher=Massachusetts Historical Society|accessdate=July 6, 2016|date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Botts appeared on stage during speeches by Sumner and other abolitionists. On May 19 and 20, 1856, Sumner spoke in the Senate, comparing Southern political positions to the sexual exploitation of slaves then taking place in the South. Two days later [[Caning of Charles Sumner|Sumner was beaten almost to death]] on the floor of the Senate in the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]] by Representative [[Preston Brooks]] from Georgia, known as a hothead.<ref name=\"Ida May\"/>\n\nThree decades after the [[Emancipation Proclamation]], [[Frances Harper]]'s 1892 novel ''[[Iola Leroy, or Shadows Uplifted]] tells the story of a \"colored\" family before and after emancipation. With the exception of Iola's grandmother, who is \"unmistakably colored\",<ref>{{citation|title=Iola Leroy, or Shadows Uplifted|at=p.&nbsp;206|language=en|url=https://docsouth.unc.edu/southlit/harper/harper.html#p206|access-date=2020-04-13\n}}</ref> all members of the family have so much European ancestry that they can easily [[Passing (racial identity)|pass for white]]. When Iola's uncle, Robert Johnson, escapes from slavery and distinguishes himself in the Union army, a white officer compares him to the other former slaves among his soldiers: \"You do not look like them, you do not talk like them. It is a burning shame to have held such a man as you in slavery.\" Johnson answers: \"I don't think it was any worse to have held me in slavery than the blackest man in the South.\"<ref>{{citation|title=Iola Leroy, or Shadows Uplifted|at=p.&nbsp;44|language=en|url=https://docsouth.unc.edu/southlit/harper/harper.html#p44|access-date=2020-04-13\n}}</ref>\n\n===Nonfiction===\nNonfiction accounts written by escaped mixed-race slaves who used their European appearance to \"pass for white\" and gain freedom include [[Ellen Craft]]: ''Running a Thousand Miles for Freedom'' (coauthored with her husband William).<ref name=\"Craft\">{{cite book|last1=Craft|first1=William and Ellen|title=Running a Thousand Miles for Freedom|date=1860|pages=63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0znsAgAAQBAJ|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> With majority-white ancestry, Craft often also appeared as a speaker on the abolitionist lecture circuit.<ref name=\"McCaskill\">[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-622 Barbara McCaskill, \"William and Ellen Craft\"], ''New Georgia Encyclopedia'', 2010, accessed July 6, 2016</ref>\n\nThe Crafts and other abolitionists also publicized the life of [[Sally Miller|Salom\u00e9 M\u00fcller]], a German immigrant orphaned as an infant soon after arrival in New Orleans. Though Muller (later known as Sally Miller) was completely of European descent, she became enslaved as an infant, treated as a mixed-race slave. The threat of white girls being seized and thrown into slavery prompted [[Parker Pillsbury]] to write to [[William Lloyd Garrison]]: \"A white skin is no security whatsoever. I should no more dare to send white children out to play alone, especially at night...than I should dare send them into a forest of tigers and hyenas.\"<ref name=\"Wilson\">[https://www.jstor.org/pss/4233569 Carol Wilson, \"Sally Muller, the White Slave\"], ''Louisiana History'', Vol. 40, 1999, accessed July 7, 2016</ref>\n\nFannie Virginia Casseopia Lawrence was a young white slave freed in early 1863. She was adopted by Catherine S. Lawrence of New York and baptized by [[Henry Ward Beecher]] at the Plymouth Congregational Church in Brooklyn, New York. ''Carte de visite'' photographs of her were also sold to raise money for the abolitionist cause.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Tanya Ballard|title=A Black And White 1860s Fundraiser|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/pictureshow/2012/12/10/166093470/a-black-and-white-1860s-fundraiser|website=NPR|accessdate=July 5, 2016|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=250>\nFile:Mary Mildred Botts.jpg|Mary Mildred Botts in an 1855 [[daguerreotype]]\nFile:Fannie Virginia Casseopia Lawrence 1863.jpg|Fannie Virginia Casseopia Lawrence, a slave freed in early 1863\nFile:Ellen Craft escaped slave.jpg|Etching of Ellen Craft based on a c. 1860 photo\n</gallery>\n\n===A special case: Freed slaves from Louisiana===\n[[File:Learning is Wealth.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Four former slaves - three children and an adult man, all with books in their hands; the image is entitled \"Learning is Wealth\"]]\n\nBy 1863 in Louisiana, ninety-five schools for [[freedmen]], serving 9,500 students, were active in areas controlled by the [[Union Army]]. Funding was needed to continue to run the schools. The [[National Freedman's Association]], the [[American Missionary Association]], and Union officers launched a publicity campaign to raise money by selling [[carte de visite]] (CDV) photographs of eight former slaves, five children and three adults. The former slaves were accompanied on a tour of Philadelphia and New York by Colonel [[George H. Hanks]]. A woodcut, based on a photograph of the former slaves, appeared in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'' in January 1864 with the caption \"EMANCIPATED SLAVES, WHITE AND COLORED.\"<ref name=CaustEllenbogen>{{cite web|last=Caust-Ellenbogen|first=Celia|title=White Slaves|url=http://trilogy.brynmawr.edu/speccoll/quakersandslavery/commentary/themes/white_slaves.php|publisher=[[Bryn Mawr College]], [[Swarthmore College]] |accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodman\" /> Four of the children were predominantly white in appearance, although born into slavery. \n\nThe former slaves traveled from [[New Orleans]] to the North. Of these, four children appeared to be white or [[octoroon]]. According to the ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'' article, they were, {{\" '}}perfectly white;' 'very fair;' 'of unmixed white race.' Their light complexions contrasted sharply with those of the three adults, Wilson, Mary, and Robert; and that of the fifth child, Isaac\u2014'a black boy of eight years; but nonetheless [more] intelligent than his whiter companions.{{' \"}}<ref name=CaustEllenbogen /><ref name=NYDN>{{cite news|title='White' slave children of New Orleans|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/white-slave-children-new-orleans-1860s-propaganda-campaign-gallery-1.1164989|accessdate=31 August 2013|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe group was accompanied by Colonel Hanks from the [[18th Infantry Regiment (United States)|18th Infantry Regiment]]. They posed for photos in [[New York City]] and in [[Philadelphia]]. The resulting images were produced in the [[carte de visite]] format and were sold for twenty-five cents each, with the profits of the sale being directed to [[Major general (United States)|Major General]] [[Nathaniel P. Banks]] back in [[Louisiana]] to support education of freedmen. Each of the photos noted that sale proceeds would be \"devoted to the education of colored people\".<ref name=CaustEllenbogen /><ref name=NYDN />\n\nOf the many prints that were commissioned, at least twenty-two remain in existence today. Most of these were produced by Charles Paxson and Myron Kimball, who took the group photo that later appeared as a woodcut in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]''. A portrait of Rebecca was taken by James E. McClees of Philadelphia.<ref name=CaustEllenbogen />\n\n==Modern analysis==\n[[File:Freedoms Banner Charley a slave boy from New Orelans 1864.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Charley Taylor holding an American flag.  Charley was the son of [[Alexander Withers]] and one of Withers's slaves.  Withers sold Charley to a slave dealer and he was sold again in New Orleans.]]\n\nModern scholars have examined the white slave campaign's motives and success. Mary Niall Mitchell, in \"Rosebloom and Pure White, Or So It Seemed,\"<ref name=\"mnm\">{{cite web|last1=Mitchell|first1=Mary Niall|title='Rosebloom and Pure White,' Or So It Seemed|url=http://scholarworks.uno.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1003&context=hist_facpubs|website=ScholarWorks@UNO|publisher=University of New Orleans|accessdate=June 29, 2016}} also published in  American Quarterly 54:3 (September 2002): 369-410</ref> argues that because the slaves were depicted as being white, through both their skin color and style of dress, abolitionists could argue that the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] was independent of class status. Supporters of the war believed that this was needed after [[New York City draft riots|the draft riots]] in [[New York City]] that year. Predominantly ethnic Irish mobs had protested the draft law, as wealthier men could buy substitutes rather than serve in the war.\n\nCarol Goodman, in \"Visualizing the Color Line,\" has argued that the photos alluded to physical and sexual abuse of the children's mothers. When publishing the photo of the eight former slaves, the editor of ''Harper's Weekly'' wrote that slavery permits slave-holding \"'gentlemen' [to] seduce [the] most friendless and defenseless of women.\" The specter of \"white\" girls being sold as \"fancy girls\" or [[concubines]] in Southern slave markets may have caused Northern families to fear for the safely of their own daughters. Similarly, the idea that white slave-master fathers would sell their own children in slave markets raised Northerners' concerns.\n\n[[Gwendolyn DuBois Shaw]], in \"Portraits of a People,\" has argued that the usage of props, such as the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] and books, helped to provide context for Northern viewers, and also to emphasize that the purpose of the photos was to raise money for education of former slaves by funding schools in [[Louisiana]]. She also noted that the use of \"white\" children to illustrate the damage caused by institutional slavery, whose victims were overwhelmingly visibly people of color, demonstrated the contemporary racism of both Southern and Northern societies.<ref name=CaustEllenbogen />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Julia Chinn]]\n*[[Louisa Picquet]]\n*[[Mary Mildred Williams]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenzer|first1=Lawrence Raymond|title=The Forgotten Cause of the Civil War: A New Look at the Slavery Issue|date=1997|publisher=Scholars' Publishing House|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EGkOAQAAMAAJ}} See especially [http://multiracial.com/site/index.php/2001/10/01/white-slaves/ Ch.III]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=p5U-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA32-IA29&lpg=PA32-IA29#v=onepage&q&f=false Fremont Campaign Literature, 1856]\n*[[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], [http://www.theroot.com/articles/history/2013/02/how_mixed_are_african_americans/ Exactly How \u2018Black\u2019 Is Black America?]\n*{{cite book|last1=Janken|first1=Kenneth Robert|title=Walter White: Mr. NAACP|date=2006|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=9780807857809|pages=3\u20135|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cTVZ6N9vHxsC}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|White slave propaganda}}\n{{Wikisource-inline|The Barbarism of Slavery}}\n*[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/white-slave-children-new-orleans-1860s-propaganda-campaign-gallery-1.1164989?pmSlide=0 Image gallery]\n\n[[Category:Abolitionism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Colorism]]\n[[Category:Propaganda in the United States]]\n[[Category:Skin pigmentation]]\n[[Category:Slavery in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rsk6400", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFiction:Corrected italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_slave_propaganda"}
{"title_page": "Lynis", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Lynis\n| ver layout = simple\n| genre                  = [[Security Software]], [[Audit]] tool\n| license                = [[GNU GPLv3]]\n| latest_release_version = 2.7.5\n| latest_release_date    = {{Start date and age|2019|6|24|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/CISOfy/lynis/releases|title=Releases - CISOfy/lynis|accessdate=25 June 2019|via=[[GitHub]]}}</ref>\n| operating_system       = [[FreeBSD]], [[Linux]], [[macOS]], [[OpenBSD]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]]\n| programming language = [[Shell script]]\n| author = Michael Boelen\n| developer = [[CISOfy]]\n}}\n\n'''Lynis''' is an extensible security [[Information security audit|audit tool]] for computer systems running [[Linux]], [[FreeBSD]], [[macOS]], [[OpenBSD]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]], and other Unix-derivatives. It assists [[system administrators]] and security professionals with scanning a system and its security defenses, with the final goal being [[hardening (computing)|system hardening]].<ref name = \"Vigo, TechRepublic, 2019\" > {{ cite web | url = https://www.techrepublic.com/article/how-to-harden-your-macos-systems-with-lynis/ | title = How to harden your macOS systems with Lynis | access-date = 15 July 2019 | first = Jesus | last = Vigo | date = 2 June 2019 | website = [[TechRepublic]] | quote = Lynis is different to other, more popular security packages such as Nessus and OpenVAS, in that while the latter both focus on assessing vulnerabilities for the purposes of exploiting the findings; the former analyzes systems and compares the findings to a known set of ever-expanding criteria in an effort to determine an index, or score, that is assigned to systems after a number of checks have been completed and how the device compares to the criteria of known best practices. | format = html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190603051628/https://www.techrepublic.com/article/how-to-harden-your-macos-systems-with-lynis/ | archive-date = 3 June 2019 | df = dmy-all }} </ref>\n\n==Software==\nThe tool was created by Michael Boelen, the original author of [[rkhunter]] as well as several special contributors and translators.<ref name = \"Lynis - CONTRIBUTORS\" >{{cite web | url=https://fossies.org/dox/lynis-2.4.6/md_CONTRIBUTORS.html | title=lynis: Lynis - CONTRIBUTORS - doxygen documentation - Fossies Dox | publisher=M. Boelen, fossies.org | date=2017-03-15 | accessdate=2017-03-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170320144151/https://fossies.org/dox/lynis-2.4.6/md_CONTRIBUTORS.html | archive-date = 20 March 2017 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Lynis is available under the [[GNU General Public License#Version 3|GPLv3]] license.\n\nThe software determines various system information, such as the specific OS type, kernel parameters, authentication and accounting mechanism, installed packages, installed [[daemon (computing)|services]], network configuration, logging and monitoring (e.g. [[syslog-ng]]), cryptography (e.g. [[Public key certificate|SSL/TLS certificates]]) and installed malware scanners (e.g. [[Clam AntiVirus|ClamAV]] or [[rkhunter]]). Additionally, it will check the system for [[configuration management|configuration]] errors and security issues. By request of the auditor, those checks may conform to international standards such as [[ISO/IEC 27001:2005|ISO 27001]], [[Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard|PCI-DSS 3.2]] and [[HIPAA]].\n\nThe software also helps with fully automated or semi-automatic auditing, software patch management, evaluation of server hardening guidelines and [[vulnerability (computing)|vulnerability]]/[[malware]] scanning of Unix-based systems. It can be locally installed from most system [[package manager#Repositories|repositories]], or directly started from disk, including USB stick, CD or DVD.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tecmint.com/linux-security-auditing-and-scanning-with-lynis-tool/ | title=Lynis 2.2.0 Released \u2013 Security Auditing and Scanning Tool for Linux Systems | publisher=Ravi Saive, tecmint.com | date=2016-03-18 | accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Audience==\nThe intended audience is [[auditor]]s, security specialists, [[penetration test]]ers, and sometimes system/network administrators. Usually members of a [[:de:Three-Lines-of-Defense-Modell|First Line of Defense]] within a company or larger organization tend to employ such audit tools. According to the official documentation, there is also a Lynis Enterprise version, available with support for more than 10 computer systems, providing malware scanning, intrusion detection and additional guidance for auditors.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://github.com/CISOfy/lynis/blob/master/README | title=Lynis/README at master \u00b7 CISOfy/lynis \u00b7 GitHub | publisher=M. Boelen, GitHub | date=2017-03-15 | accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn 2016, Lynis won an ''[[InfoWorld]]'' Bossie Award.<ref>http://www.infoworld.com/article/3121251/open-source-tools/bossie-awards-2016-the-best-open-source-networking-and-security-software.html#slide13</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[chkrootkit]]\n* [[Host-based intrusion detection system comparison]]\n*[[List of free and open-source software packages]]\n* [[Kali Linux]]<ref>[https://tools.kali.org/vulnerability-analysis/lynis Kali tools, Lynis Package Description]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://freecode.com/projects/lynis/ Lynis on free(code)]\n* {{github|CISOfy/lynis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lynis}}\n[[Category:Free security software]]\n[[Category:Unix security-related software]]\n[[Category:Unix package management-related software]]\n[[Category:MacOS security software]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Lynis\n| ver layout = simple\n| genre                  = [[Security Software]], [[Audit]] tool\n| license                = [[GNU GPLv3]]\n| latest_release_version = 2.7.5\n| latest_release_date    = {{Start date and age|2019|6|24|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/CISOfy/lynis/releases|title=Releases - CISOfy/lynis|accessdate=25 June 2019|via=[[GitHub]]}}</ref>\n| operating_system       = [[FreeBSD]], [[Linux]], [[macOS]], [[OpenBSD]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]]\n| programming language = [[Shell script]]\n| author = Michael Boelen\n| developer = [[CISOfy]]\n}}\n\n'''Lynis''' is an extensible security [[information technology security audit|audit tool]] for computer systems running [[Linux]], [[FreeBSD]], [[macOS]], [[OpenBSD]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]], and other Unix-derivatives. It assists [[system administrators]] and security professionals with scanning a system and its security defenses, with the final goal being [[hardening (computing)|system hardening]].<ref name = \"Vigo, TechRepublic, 2019\" > {{ cite web | url = https://www.techrepublic.com/article/how-to-harden-your-macos-systems-with-lynis/ | title = How to harden your macOS systems with Lynis | access-date = 15 July 2019 | first = Jesus | last = Vigo | date = 2 June 2019 | website = [[TechRepublic]] | quote = Lynis is different to other, more popular security packages such as Nessus and OpenVAS, in that while the latter both focus on assessing vulnerabilities for the purposes of exploiting the findings; the former analyzes systems and compares the findings to a known set of ever-expanding criteria in an effort to determine an index, or score, that is assigned to systems after a number of checks have been completed and how the device compares to the criteria of known best practices. | format = html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190603051628/https://www.techrepublic.com/article/how-to-harden-your-macos-systems-with-lynis/ | archive-date = 3 June 2019 | df = dmy-all }} </ref>\n\n==Software==\nThe tool was created by Michael Boelen, the original author of [[rkhunter]] as well as several special contributors and translators.<ref name = \"Lynis - CONTRIBUTORS\" >{{cite web | url=https://fossies.org/dox/lynis-2.4.6/md_CONTRIBUTORS.html | title=lynis: Lynis - CONTRIBUTORS - doxygen documentation - Fossies Dox | publisher=M. Boelen, fossies.org | date=2017-03-15 | accessdate=2017-03-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170320144151/https://fossies.org/dox/lynis-2.4.6/md_CONTRIBUTORS.html | archive-date = 20 March 2017 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Lynis is available under the [[GNU General Public License#Version 3|GPLv3]] license.\n\nThe software determines various system information, such as the specific OS type, kernel parameters, authentication and accounting mechanism, installed packages, installed [[daemon (computing)|services]], network configuration, logging and monitoring (e.g. [[syslog-ng]]), cryptography (e.g. [[Public key certificate|SSL/TLS certificates]]) and installed malware scanners (e.g. [[Clam AntiVirus|ClamAV]] or [[rkhunter]]). Additionally, it will check the system for [[configuration management|configuration]] errors and security issues. By request of the auditor, those checks may conform to international standards such as [[ISO/IEC 27001:2005|ISO 27001]], [[Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard|PCI-DSS 3.2]] and [[HIPAA]].\n\nThe software also helps with fully automated or semi-automatic auditing, software patch management, evaluation of server hardening guidelines and [[vulnerability (computing)|vulnerability]]/[[malware]] scanning of Unix-based systems. It can be locally installed from most system [[package manager#Repositories|repositories]], or directly started from disk, including USB stick, CD or DVD.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tecmint.com/linux-security-auditing-and-scanning-with-lynis-tool/ | title=Lynis 2.2.0 Released \u2013 Security Auditing and Scanning Tool for Linux Systems | publisher=Ravi Saive, tecmint.com | date=2016-03-18 | accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Audience==\nThe intended audience is [[auditor]]s, security specialists, [[penetration test]]ers, and sometimes system/network administrators. Usually members of a [[:de:Three-Lines-of-Defense-Modell|First Line of Defense]] within a company or larger organization tend to employ such audit tools. According to the official documentation, there is also a Lynis Enterprise version, available with support for more than 10 computer systems, providing malware scanning, intrusion detection and additional guidance for auditors.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://github.com/CISOfy/lynis/blob/master/README | title=Lynis/README at master \u00b7 CISOfy/lynis \u00b7 GitHub | publisher=M. Boelen, GitHub | date=2017-03-15 | accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn 2016, Lynis won an ''[[InfoWorld]]'' Bossie Award.<ref>http://www.infoworld.com/article/3121251/open-source-tools/bossie-awards-2016-the-best-open-source-networking-and-security-software.html#slide13</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[chkrootkit]]\n* [[Host-based intrusion detection system comparison]]\n*[[List of free and open-source software packages]]\n* [[Kali Linux]]<ref>[https://tools.kali.org/vulnerability-analysis/lynis Kali tools, Lynis Package Description]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://freecode.com/projects/lynis/ Lynis on free(code)]\n* {{github|CISOfy/lynis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lynis}}\n[[Category:Free security software]]\n[[Category:Unix security-related software]]\n[[Category:Unix package management-related software]]\n[[Category:MacOS security software]]\n", "name_user": "Jukeboksi", "label": "safe", "comment": "unredirecting link toInformation security audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lynis"}
{"title_page": "World Rowing U23 Championships", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n'''World Rowing U23 Championships'''  is an international [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] [[regatta]] organized by [[International Rowing Federation|FISA]] (the International Rowing Federation).  It is a week-long event for best rowers under 23 year age.\n\n==History==\nFrom 1976 the U23 event was organised as the Nations Cup, independently from FISA. In 2002 it became the World Rowing U23 Regatta, before becoming the Championships from 2005.\n\n==Venues==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=#CCDDEE \n! Ed.\n! Year\n! City\n! Country\n! Date\n! Nations\n|-\n| 1 || [[2005 World Rowing U23 Championships|2005]] || [[Amsterdam]] || {{flag|Netherlands}} || 21\u201324 July || \n|-\n| 2 || [[2006 World Rowing U23 Championships|2006]] || [[Hazewinkel]] || {{flag|Belgium}} || 20\u201323 July ||\n|-\n| 3 || [[2007 World Rowing U23 Championships|2007]] || [[Glasgow]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}} || 26\u201329 July ||\n|-\n| 4 || [[2008 World Rowing U23 Championships|2008]] || [[Brandenburg]] || {{flag|Germany}} || 17\u201320 July ||\n|-\n| 5 || [[2009 World Rowing U23 Championships|2009]] || [[Ra\u010dice (Litom\u011b\u0159ice District)|Ra\u010dice]] || {{flag|Czech Republic}} || 26\u201329 July ||\n|-\n| 6 || [[2010 World Rowing U23 Championships|2010]] || [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]] || {{flag|Belarus}} || 22\u201325 July || 58\n|-\n| 7 || [[2011 World Rowing U23 Championships|2011]] || [[Amsterdam]] || {{flag|Netherlands}} || 20\u201324 July || 63\n|-\n| 8 || [[2012 World Rowing U23 Championships|2012]] || [[Trakai]] || {{flag|Lithuania}} || 11\u201315 July || 55\n|-\n| 9 || [[2013 World Rowing U23 Championships|2013]] || [[Linz]]-[[Ottensheim]] || {{flag|Austria}} || 24\u201328 July ||\n|-\n| 10 || [[2014 World Rowing U23 Championships|2014]] || [[Varese]] || {{flag|Italy}} || 23\u201327 July ||\n|-\n| 11 || [[2015 World Rowing U23 Championships|2015]] || [[Plovdiv]] || {{flag|Bulgaria}} || 22\u201326 July ||\n|-\n| 12 || [[2016 World Rowing U23 Championships|2016]] || [[Rotterdam]] || {{flag|Netherlands}} || 21\u201328 August || \n|-\n| 13 || [[2017 World Rowing U23 Championships|2017]] || [[Plovdiv]] || {{flag|Bulgaria}} || 19\u201323 July || \n|-\n| 14 || [[2018 World Rowing U23 Championships|2018]] || [[Pozna\u0144]] || {{flag|Poland}} || 25\u201329 July || \n|-\n| 15 || [[2019 World Rowing U23 Championships|2019]] || [[Sarasota]] || {{flag|USA}} || 24\u201328 July || \n|-\n| 16 || [[2020 World Rowing U23 Championships|2020]] || [[Bled]] || {{flag|SLO}} || 16\u201323 August [cancelled]<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 World Rowing regatta season : the continued consequences of COVID-19 global pandemic |url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/2020-world-rowing-regatta-season-the-continued-consequences-covid-global-pandemic |website=worldrowing.com |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldrowing.com/ World Rowing website]\n\n{{Rowing Competitions}}\n{{Rowing (sport)}}\n\n[[Category:World Rowing U23 Championships| ]]\n[[Category:Rowing competitions]]\n[[Category:Under-23 sports competitions]]\n[[Category:World youth sports competitions]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2005]]\n\n\n{{rowing-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n'''World Rowing U23 Championships'''  is an international [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] [[regatta]] organized by [[International Rowing Federation|FISA]] (the International Rowing Federation).  It is a week-long event for best rowers under 23 year age.\n\n==History==\nFrom 1976 the U23 event was organised as the Nations Cup, independently from FISA. In 2002 it became the World Rowing U23 Regatta, before becoming the Championships from 2005.\n\n==Venues==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=#CCDDEE \n! Ed.\n! Year\n! City\n! Country\n! Date\n!